<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Notes</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Myrtaceae" genus="Psidium" higherTaxonomySource="IPNI" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Psidium guajava" order="Myrtales" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="species" species="guajava">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878">Psidium guajava</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a native of Central and South America, is widely cultivated in tropical and subtropical regions around the world for its edible fruits (guava). It easily escapes wherever introduced. In the Canary Islands, it was first reported from various localities in La Palma (
<bibRefCitation author="Santos Guerra, A" journalOrPublisher="Vieraea" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" pagination="249 - 258" refId="B6509566" refString="Santos Guerra, A, Reyes-Betancort, JA, 2014. Nuevas adiciones y citas de interes para la flora autoctona de las islas Canarias. Vieraea 42: 249 - 258" title="Nuevas adiciones y citas de interes para la flora autoctona de las islas Canarias" volume="42" year="2014">Santos Guerra and Reyes-Betancort 2014</bibRefCitation>
), shortly afterwards also from Gran Canaria (
<bibRefCitation author="Verloove, F" journalOrPublisher="Acta Botanica Croatica" pageId="0" pageNumber="62878" pagination="120 - 131" refId="B6509982" refString="Verloove, F, 2017. New xenophytes from the Canary Islands (Gran Canaria and Tenerife; Spain). Acta Botanica Croatica 76 (2): 120 - 131" title="New xenophytes from the Canary Islands (Gran Canaria and Tenerife; Spain)" volume="76" year="2017">Verloove 2017</bibRefCitation>
). It is mostly found in dried-out riverbeds where it germinates from wastewater. In such circumstances, it was also recently found for the first time in Tenerife.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
